'''awesome''' is a highly configurable, next generation framework window manager for X. It is primarly targeted at power users, developers and any people dealing with every day computing tasks and who want to have fine-grained control on theirs graphical environment.

== Installation ==
{{Emerge|x11-wm/awesome}}

== Keyboard shortcuts ==
<pre>
mod4 + enter = open terminal
mod4 + r = run command
mod4 + shift + c = kill
mod4 + m = maximize
mod4 + f = fullscreen
mod4 + ctrl + space = float / tile

mod4 + j = hilight left client
mod4 + k = hilight right client

mod4 + shift + j = move client right
mod4 + shift + k = move client left

mod4 + l = resize tiled client
mod4 + h = resize tiled client

mod + 1-9 = change tag
mod + shift + 1-9 = send client to tag

mod4 + mouse1 = move client with mouse
mod4 + mouse2 = resize client with mouse
</pre>

== Configuration ==
Its useful to check config file for errors before restarting awesome.
{{Cmd|awesome -k rc.lua|output=✔ Configuration file syntax OK.}}


The default configuration file of '''Awesome''' is located in '''''~/.config/awesome/rc.lua'''''. If such a directory or file does not exist we will need to create them.

=== Creating the configuration ===
A default, out of the box, configuration is distributed with '''Awesome''' and can be found at '''''/etc/xdg/awesome/rc.lua'''''. We would need to copy that configuration file to the user home directory.<br \>
First we create the '''awesome''' directory with the following command:
{{Cmd| mkdir ~/.config/awesome/}}
Then we copy the ''lua'' configuration file with the following command:
{{Cmd| cp /etc/xdg/awesome/rc.lua ~/.config/awesome/rc.lua}}

=== Tags ===
{{file|rc.conf||Example of 4 tags with custom numbers
<pre>
-- {{{ Tags
tags = {}
for s = 1, screen.count() do
    tags[s] = awful.tag({ "➊", "➋", "➌", "➍" }, s, layouts[1])
end
-- }}}
</pre>}}

=== Menu ===
{{file|rc.conf||Example of simple custom menu
<pre>
-- {{{ Menu
myawesomemenu = {
   { "manual", terminal .. " -e man awesome" },
   { "edit config", editor_cmd .. " " .. awesome.conffile },
   { "restart", awesome.restart },
   { "quit", awesome.quit }
}

appsmenu = {
   { "urxvt", "urxvt" },
   { "luakit", "luakit" },
   { "uzbl", "uzbl-browser" },
   { "thunar", "thunar" },
   { "gedit", "gedit" },
}

mymainmenu = awful.menu({ items = { { "awesome", myawesomemenu },
                                    { "apps", appsmenu },
                                    { "terminal", terminal }
                                  }
                        })

mylauncher = awful.widget.launcher({ image = image(beautiful.awesome_icon),
                                     menu = mymainmenu })
-- }}}
</pre>}}

=== Date ===

{{file|rc.conf||Example of custom date
<pre>
-- {{{ Wibox
-- Create a textclock widget
mytextclock = awful.widget.textclock({ align = "right" }," %d.%m %H:%M ", 60)
</pre>}}

=== Launch ===
If '''awesome''' is going to be launched from terminal through '''''startx''''' a configuration similar to the following is needed:
{{File|~/.xinitrc||<pre>
<nowiki>exec /usr/bin/ck-launch-session /usr/bin/dbus-launch /usr/bin/awesome
</nowiki></pre>
}}
==== Touchpad ====
If a '''Touchpad''' hardware is present and scrolling does not work ''.xinitrc'' should look similar to the following:
{{File|~/.xinitrc||<pre>
<nowiki>synclient HorizEdgeScroll=1
synclient VertEdgeScroll=1
synclient TapButton1=1
exec /usr/bin/ck-launch-session /usr/bin/dbus-launch /usr/bin/awesome</nowiki></pre>
}}

{{Note| '''synclient''' belongs to {{Package|x11-drivers/xf86-input-synaptics}}}}

